;; Book of Arcade Games — Chapter 14: The Coin-Op Loop

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Arcade Games"
  :chapter-number      14
  :title               "The Coin-Op Loop"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "arcade-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + game-design"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"A real arcade cabinet doesn't sit idle. It cycles: attract mode →
title screen → press start → play → game over → high score entry →
back to attract mode. The whole life of the machine is a state
machine. When no one is playing, the attract mode plays a demo of the
game to LURE someone to insert a quarter. When someone plays, the
game runs. When they lose, high-score entry captures their initials,
then the machine slips back to attract.

This chapter builds that whole cabinet in about 150 lines. The state
machine is a `game/state` value with transitions driven by
`input/pressed? 'a`. Each state has its own paint and its own logic.
Between states, one moment of blank + reset.

By the end you have a shippable arcade session — everything from title
to leaderboard.

---

## 14.1 States

The cabinet has five states:

- `'attract` — demo playing, waits for start button
- `'title` — title screen with menu
- `'play` — the actual game
- `'game-over` — end screen, brief pause
- `'high-score` — high-score entry

Each has an entry action, a per-frame action, and transitions.

```scheme
(define cabinet-state 'attract)
(define state-timer 0)
```

---

## 14.2 Title screen

Slow breathing animation on 'PRESS START'.

```scheme
(define (paint-title-screen)
  (paint-clear)
  (paint-text \"BALLPIT\" 120 60)
  (paint-text \"the arcade\" 130 80)
  ;; Breathing 'PRESS START' via tick/sine.
  (let* ((phase (* 0.05 (world/frame)))
         (breath (+ 1.0 (* 0.15 (tick/sine phase))))
         (x-offset (round (* breath 130))))
    (paint-text \"PRESS START\" x-offset 140))
  (paint-text \"HIGH: \"
              80 190)
  (paint-text (number->string (or (cortex/read 'arcade-high) 0))
              140 190))
```

`tick/sine phase` returns a sine wave value oscillating between -1
and 1. Multiplied by 0.15 and added to 1.0, gives a factor from 0.85
to 1.15. Times a base position, the text subtly breathes.

Kids read this animation as 'the game is alive, waiting for me.'
Static text feels dead.

---

## 14.3 Play

The actual game — we'll use the small ball-bounce game from chapter 1
for simplicity, but this slot holds whichever chapter's shape you like.

```scheme
(define (init-play)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.4)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'triangle 8)
    (entity/solid! p #t))
  (set! current-score 0)
  (set! player-hp 3))

(define current-score 0)
(define player-hp 3)

(define (paint-play)
  (world/step)
  (paint-clear)
  (world/each 'player
              (lambda (p) (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8)))
  (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \" (number->string current-score)) 10 10)
  (paint-text (string-append \"HP: \" (number->string player-hp)) 10 20))
```

Real play code goes here. For a shippable demo, replace with the boss
fight from chapter 12 or the shmup from chapter 5.

---

## 14.4 Game over

Brief pause with the final score.

```scheme
(define (paint-game-over)
  (paint-clear)
  (paint-text \"GAME OVER\" 120 100)
  (paint-text (string-append \"Final: \" (number->string current-score))
              110 130)
  (paint-text (string-append \"Time to attract mode: \"
                             (number->string (max 0 (- 180 state-timer))))
              60 200))
```

180 frames = 3 seconds. Long enough to absorb. Short enough that a
disengaged player doesn't stall.

---

## 14.5 High score entry

If final score beats the top-5 board, capture the player's initials.

```scheme
(define high-score-initials \"AAA\")
(define initial-cursor 0)     ;; which letter (0, 1, 2)

(define (paint-high-score-entry)
  (paint-clear)
  (paint-text \"NEW HIGH SCORE!\" 100 60)
  (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \" (number->string current-score))
              120 90)
  (paint-text \"Enter your initials\" 90 130)
  ;; Draw each of 3 initial letters. Highlight the cursor position.
  (let loop ((i 0))
    (when (< i 3)
      (let ((letter (string (string-ref high-score-initials i)))
            (x (+ 140 (* i 16))))
        (paint-text letter x 160)
        (when (= i initial-cursor)
          (paint-text \"_\" x 165)))     ;; underscore for cursor
      (loop (+ i 1)))))

(define (advance-initial delta)
  (let* ((cur (char->integer (string-ref high-score-initials initial-cursor)))
         (next (+ cur delta))
         (wrapped (cond ((< next 65) 90) ((> next 90) 65) (else next)))
         (str (make-string 3)))
    (string-set! str 0 (string-ref high-score-initials 0))
    (string-set! str 1 (string-ref high-score-initials 1))
    (string-set! str 2 (string-ref high-score-initials 2))
    (string-set! str initial-cursor (integer->char wrapped))
    (set! high-score-initials str)))
```

Up/down cycles through letters A-Z. Left/right moves cursor. 'a' saves
to Cortex leaderboard.

---

## 14.6 The state machine

Wire it all together.

```scheme
(define cabinet-state 'attract)
(define state-timer 0)

(define (transition new-state)
  (set! cabinet-state new-state)
  (set! state-timer 0)
  (when (eq? new-state 'play)
    (init-play)))

(define (arcade-cabinet)
  (transition 'attract)
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     (set! state-timer (+ state-timer 1))
     (cond
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'attract)
        ;; Attract mode: play the game silently in background, wait
        ;; for start button. For simplicity we just show the title.
        (paint-title-screen)
        (when (input/pressed? 'a) (transition 'play))
        ;; After 20 seconds of attract, show a demo (chapter 14, App K).
        )
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'title)
        (paint-title-screen)
        (when (input/pressed? 'a) (transition 'play)))
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'play)
        (when (input/down? 'left)
          (world/each 'player (lambda (p) (entity/move! p -4 0))))
        (when (input/down? 'right)
          (world/each 'player (lambda (p) (entity/move! p 4 0))))
        (when (input/pressed? 'a)
          (set! current-score (+ current-score 100)))
        (paint-play)
        ;; Simulated game-over: 30 sec of play, or press 'b'.
        (when (or (> state-timer (* 60 30)) (input/pressed? 'b))
          (transition 'game-over)))
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'game-over)
        (paint-game-over)
        (when (> state-timer 180)
          (if (> current-score (or (cortex/read 'arcade-high) 0))
              (transition 'high-score)
              (transition 'attract))))
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'high-score)
        (paint-high-score-entry)
        (when (input/pressed? 'left)
          (set! initial-cursor (max 0 (- initial-cursor 1))))
        (when (input/pressed? 'right)
          (set! initial-cursor (min 2 (+ initial-cursor 1))))
        (when (input/pressed? 'up)   (advance-initial 1))
        (when (input/pressed? 'down) (advance-initial -1))
        (when (input/pressed? 'a)
          (cortex/write 'arcade-high current-score)
          (cortex/write 'arcade-initials high-score-initials)
          (transition 'attract)))))))

(big-bang arcade-cabinet)
```

Read the `cond` slowly. Each branch handles ONE state. Each branch
paints, polls input, and possibly transitions. Between states, one
frame of setup via `transition`.

`init-play` resets the world. That is the key discipline of a state
machine: each state entry cleans up cleanly. No leftover entities from
the previous game. No leftover state.

---

## 14.7 Attract mode with a demo

The real attract mode plays a demo of the game — recorded input replayed
back at attract time. `world/tape-record!` records inputs; `world/tape-
replay` plays them back. See Appendix K (Tape Replay for Attract Mode)
for the full pattern.

Sketch:

```scheme
;; During play, record.
(world/tape-record! 'demo-play)
;; ... game runs ...
(world/tape-save 'demo-play 'saved-demo)

;; During attract, replay.
(world/tape-replay 'saved-demo)
```

The kid does not immediately see the game. They see A game playing
itself. Muscle memory activates before they realize they're not
playing yet. Then they press start and they ARE playing.

---

## 14.8 The four patterns in a cabinet loop

**Composition.** Each state composes: paint routine + per-frame logic
+ transition condition. Add a new state (e.g. 'options-menu) by
composing a new triple.

**Orchestration.** The frame loop dispatches to the current state
each frame. Each state handles its own per-frame update, poll, paint.

**In-routing.** Input routes to state-specific handlers. 'a' in
attract = start; 'a' in play = fire; 'a' in high-score = save. Same
button, different route per state.

**Routing.** State transitions route via `transition` function. It's
the routing hub. Every transition IS a route from state to state.
Cortex writes route to persistence.

---

## 14.9 Common desktop tasks

**Shop cycle.** A shop's front page could operate as an attract loop:
demo tour → featured items → 'CLICK TO BROWSE' → item detail →
add-to-cart → checkout → thanks → back to demo. Each phase = a state.
Same pattern.

**Support-chat auto-cycle.** For an operator's chat window: idle
attract (rotating tips) → active chat → transcript summary → back to
idle. Chapter 14's shape scales.

---

## 14.10 Pitfalls

**State leaks entities.** `init-play` didn't `world/reset!`. Old boss
still on screen during title.

**Two states fire same frame.** You transitioned mid-cond and the
new state's branch also fires. Use `unless (state-changed)` guard,
or transition-only-on-last-line-of-branch.

**High-score entry saves initials without saving score.** Two Cortex
writes; if either fails, half-state. Wrap in `cortex/transaction!` if
available, or accept the risk for a small game.

**Attract mode too long.** Kids get bored. Cap at 30 seconds; loop
title-then-attract-then-title.

**Game timer runs during pause.** If your state timer counts frames,
it counts during pause menu. Freeze via `game/stop` or gate with
`(unless paused? (set! timer ...))`.

---

## 14.11 Try this yourself

1. Add an options menu — sound on/off, difficulty. State: 'options.
2. Add a credits screen — state: 'credits.
3. Multi-slot save: 3 named save slots. Kid picks which slot at
   title.
4. Difficulty scaling based on high-score history: if the player
   consistently beats top-3, increase enemy count 20%.
5. Achievements: on certain milestones (first boss kill, 10k score),
   flash achievement banner over 60 frames.
6. Cabinet 'coin' — require 3 button presses (as the arcade 'insert
   coin') before play starts. Just for atmosphere.

---

## 14.12 What we built

Five-state cabinet loop. Breathing title. Play. Game over with delay.
High-score entry. Cortex persistence of high score. Transition
discipline that resets cleanly. Full shape of an arcade session.

Next chapter: two players, one screen. Split the input space, split
the camera, share the physics. Local multiplayer.")

(code-block :chapter 14 :lang "scheme" :source
"(define cabinet-state 'attract)
(define state-timer 0)
(define current-score 0)
(define (init-play)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.4)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'triangle 8)
    (entity/solid! p #t))
  (set! current-score 0))
(define (transition new-state)
  (set! cabinet-state new-state)
  (set! state-timer 0)
  (when (eq? new-state 'play) (init-play)))
(define (coin-op-anchor)
  (transition 'attract)
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     (set! state-timer (+ state-timer 1))
     (cond
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'attract)
        (paint-clear)
        (paint-text \"BALLPIT\" 120 60)
        (paint-text \"PRESS START\"
                    (+ 100 (round (* 20 (tick/sine (* 0.05 (world/frame))))))
                    140)
        (when (input/pressed? 'a) (transition 'play)))
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'play)
        (world/each 'player
                    (lambda (p)
                      (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -4 0))
                      (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 4 0))))
        (when (input/pressed? 'a) (set! current-score (+ current-score 100)))
        (world/step)
        (paint-clear)
        (world/each 'player
                    (lambda (p) (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8)))
        (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \" (number->string current-score)) 10 10)
        (when (> state-timer 1800) (transition 'game-over)))
       ((eq? cabinet-state 'game-over)
        (paint-clear)
        (paint-text \"GAME OVER\" 120 100)
        (paint-text (string-append \"Final: \" (number->string current-score))
                    110 130)
        (when (> state-timer 180) (transition 'attract)))))))
(big-bang coin-op-anchor)")
